{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_ham_ver01/data/sn86090528/00295864655/1920070101/0447.xml":{"full_text":"CHICKAfcHA DAILY EXPRESS, CHICKASHA OKLAHOMA THURSDAY, JULY 1, 132B.I\nPAGE FOUR\nCHICKASHA DAILY EXPRESS\nGEO. II EVAN'S I'nl.lisliiT and Business Manager\nJ EDWIN POOL,\" .iruuatfiugJitlitor\nOFFICIAL \"PAPER-OFGRADY COUNTY\nKntered at the Postoffice at Chickasha, Oklahoma, a.s second class\nmall matter.\nCHICKASHA, OKLAHOMA THURSDAY, JULY 1, 1920.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES.\nUn yr, delivered by carrier. $6. 00\nblx month. M ''--3.00\nThree month. \".160\nOne month -60\nOne year by mall $4.00\nSix month by mall 2 00\nThree months by mall 1.00\nSlno'e copy\nAny erroneous reflections on\nthe character,, standing or\nreputation of any person,\nfirm or corporation and any\nmis-statement which may ap\npear In the columns of the\nExpress will be gladly cor\nrected upon Its being brought\nto the attention of the\nmanagement.\nANNOUNCEMENTS\nEXPRESS PACKAGETTES\nIIVBfl A1XTBK LOCAL NBW8\nNBWH BY Of. WIHB UAIL\nBusiness Outlook Is Bright.\nYes, there lias hern n little lightening up of credit, and! money\nin large amounts for speculative purposes is not. easily obtained.\n'I In- federal reserve hoard determined that it was lime to call a\nhull in the \"orie\" of bili priees, reckless spending anil wild in\nvest ineiils and Jienee the main who wants to launch out in a w-w\nin.eipri.se of a noli es.'.enl iai, and perhaps highly\nI in.- I.; ou :i!i;iirisl it when he seeks to shake duWII\nr\nIke iii-eessai'.v capital.\nAll i.l' this means slackening 1 1 1 of Ihe stream of business and\nI'. 1. I 1\nhOvv ic hie i ins iei'11 1 11W 11 so sunny mil sens\nUtile 1. now tlmt it is the .est thine lor Ihe country\nliaat'iliitis na\nhis hanker for\ne business\na I the\nin\nin eft hiy am\nit. ..,,1,1.1 I, Vim inieiieil rn- InliL's to have 'one on\nfrenzied pace of Ihe past year must, sooner or laler. Inn leant\ndisar-.tcr.\nThe country is now going through an era of business re-adjust -lm\niii ami, necessarily, in such a period there are conditions wh, 'h\nciiee trouble and often dismay to ihe business man but llicre is no\nreason whatever for pessimism concerning the future. Competent\nauthorities are agreed that basically business conditions are not\nMich a.s tt warrant any l'orhodings of \"hard limes\" but. on the\nc.ilrary, are full of promise of better things\nWhat is here said of tin- business situation in the country p-n-(rally\nis equally applicable to local conditions. With the brightesl\ncrop' outlook known iu years, there is no reason for this section to\nbe bothered by the bugaboo that a presidential campaign year\nmust bring bad' business.\nThe farmers of firmly county are now harvesting what appears\nto he a fine crop of wheat alfalfa has thrived this season; cotton,\nthough backward, is now growing in a manner that i, exceedingly\ngratifying to the planters, and corn has advanced to a stage that\nmakes a good crop seem practically assured.\nDevelopments in the oil territory contiguous to Chickasha are\nproceeding steadily, with a certainty that proved erriory will con\ntinue to be the scene of activity and chances that new fields will\nbe opened.\nIn the face of such prospects, why should any business man per\nmit himself to become the victim of the dumps? Can the gloomy\ntalk and play the game.\no\nAdvice to Investors.\nOwuei of Liberty bonds have repeatedly been urged by gov\nernment officials uot to trade their securities for speculative\ns-toeks, particularly oil stocks- It is pointed out that the chances\nof tin investor \"making a killing\" arc very few and far be\ntween, says the Dallas News.\nBut just how slim the, opportunity to garner riches from it\nmodest outlay actually is may only be fully realized by a persua'\nof some statistics recently given out by the savings division of the\ntreausry department. According to these figures, during the\nmonths of March and April of this year, .'!S7 oil companies with a\ntotal capitalization of $til t!,42 1.700 were organized. The total gross\nincome from the average annual production of oil in this country\nis $700,000,000. The net income is much smaller, so much smaller\niu fact that it k estimated that for these newly organized com\npanies to pay a dividend as large as n per cent on their capitaliza\ntion of $(516,424,700 they would have to own the total of the na\ntion's output. Whui they actually do own, of course, is hut a neg\nligible part of the 35(.),6o(),000 barrels produced yearly. Conse\niiiently, to return to their stockholders as much .'is per cent per\nannum, they must, develop new sources of oil amounting to about\niir0,000,00() barrels annually. In other words, they must double\nthe yearly output of the country. AVhcn it is realized Unit like com\nmercial exploitation of oil in the Coiled Stales has been going on\nfor seventy years, anil that it has been possible only by the most\nstrenuous drilling to bring the production up to its present total,\nil will be realized just how much chance these new companies have\n1u double the nation's production overnight, and, consequently,\nju si. how much chance the small oil investor has to \"hit the\nlucky.\"\nDemocratic, Oh Yes.\n.McAle-,(cr Netrs Capital To be convinced that America is in\ndeed a Democratic nation and one iu which \"lese majesty\"\nplays little it any part, one would have bad only to follow the\nmany sensational candidates here last week.\nWholesonx weleone, yet there was plenty of that. And cheer\ning, there was plenty of that, just as there would have been if a\ncouple of dull fighters were mixing it in the ring. In fact the\ngreat majority or persons accepted the camlidales tor wnat tney\nwere worth, didnl thnik of being embarrassed or overawed or\ndidn't think of obeisance or hero worslipi.\nIl was inspiring to watch the effect of the candidates, on the\npopulace.\nThere was Thomas P. Gore, 'a national figure to lie sure,\nwhether to his credit or discredit. A few gathered around him\nwhenever he stopped. Hundreds of persois at the Pittsburgh pic\nnic gave him no more than a passing glance- He might as well\nhave been a barker at a circus.\nAnd Scott lVrris. accorded one of the most brilliant of the new\ngeneration of statesmen Re passed from one group to another\nfrom one town ot another without one man taking off his hat or\nassuming lhat Scott were anything more than a mere mortal. In\nfact most of those who greeted him. from the wrinkled veteran to\nthe sun-tanned farmer, called him affectionately \"Scott' and hob\nnobbed with liim just like they were old time pals.\nAnd Congressman Harreld of Oklahoma City, was in the coun\nty. Not a handful of men took the time to go and speak to him.\nThe fact that he voted to allow Herger to remain in congress didn't\neven draw the Socialists to him for any admiration\nVerily Ihis is a country where a man is accepted as a man for\nall that. A monarch would certainly have a hard time trying to\nmake servile subjects out of the Americans of Oklahoma. They\njiM wouldn't stand it three ininntes. Americans wherever one\ntakes them, are not given to bowing down to anything or anybody,\nthank thp Lord-\nNo endeavor Is in Va!a\nThe reward in In the doing;\nAmi the rapture of pursuing\nIs the prize the vanquished gain.\nLongfellow.\nAh wo understand It, the courts\nof all civilized tiutioris have, held that\na woman luus an inherent right to\nchange her inliirl us often iim hIic\nplea hps.\nIT Mr. Ifallowell will ;o out to the\nhaaehall park Home evening uihI\nwatch the ItolarluiiH null I. Ions work\ning mil, he will discover some v;ilu:i\nlile recruits t'nr the 'hicks.\nfor instance, i: Schultz or Doc\nCrime-hot h lilg league material.\nAnd the m-w iniiiiuger 'might do\nworse than to nigh W. C, Ueljivln\nfor \"short.\"\nto the Democratic primary.\nCounty Clerk\nW. T. (BILLY) CLOUD Announces\nthat be Is a candidate for county\nclerk, subject to tbe democratic\nprimary.\nM. I. Stokes announces that